1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2 Bg7 4. e4 O-O {This rare and provocative move
deserves attention because it is an attempt by Black to avoid 5.Bb5+ 
(discussed in CHAPTER 4) . The principled reply is} 5. e5 {Advancing the
e-pawn without proper development carries its risks as the pawns can become
exposed to counterattack, but White has good resources to fight for an
initiative with this move, nevertheless.} ({White can also stick to the solid
strategy by playing} 5. Bd3 $5 {However, an obvious drawback is that Black can
freely develop the knight on c6 in the absence of Bb5 possibility. After} d6 6.
O-O Nc6 {we have a transposition into CHAPTER 2.}) 5... Nh5 $5 {The most
unusual move is the best one in this position. Nowadays even the most
antipositional of ideas can be playable with the help of engines.} (5... Ne8 $2
{is the most logical retreat, preparing to undermine white pawn centre with ...
d6, ...c5, etc., but it is wrong. I had this position against Peter Svidler
and here I was very tempted to play} 6. h4 $1 {which is the best move in the
position. I was calculating it for quite some time, but unfortunately didn't
see the key point 10.c3! (see analysis below) ,} ({so I ended up playing a
routine move} 6. Bd3 $6 {Here, the most accurate way to attack the center is}
d6 $5 ({Svidler played} 6... c5 {instead, and I obtained a stable advantage
after} 7. dxc5 Qa5 8. O-O Qxc5 9. Re1 d6 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Nc4 $14 {1/2 (51)
Eljanov,P (2655) -Svidler,P (2737) Netanya 2019}) 7. O-O {The pawn on e5
limits the opponent's pieces to some degree, so it is better to keep it there.}
({White could not claim any advantage after} 7. exd6 Nxd6 8. O-O Bf5 9. Bxf5
Nxf5 10. c3 Nd7 $11 {1-0 (19) So,W (2767) -Mamedyarov,S (2767) chess. com INT
2019}) 7... dxe5 8. dxe5 c5 9. Re1 Nc6 10. Qe2 Nc7 11. c3 Ne6 $14 {/= Black is
very solid, but White controls more space and his position is a bit more
pleasant to play.}) 6... d6 ({Attempts to slow down the advance of the h-pawn
could end in a disaster:} 6... h6 $2 7. h5 g5 8. Nxg5 $1 hxg5 9. h6 Bh8 10. h7+
Kg7 11. Qh5 $18) (6... h5 $2 7. Ng5 d6 8. e6 $16) (6... c5 $6 7. dxc5 d6 8. Nc4
$16) 7. h5 dxe5 (7... c5 {is another way to look for counterplay, but it is
too slow in the view of} 8. hxg6 hxg6 9. Nb3 $1 {White clears the diagonal for
his dark-squared bishop and launches a winning attack:} dxe5 10. Bh6 $1 cxd4
11. Bxg7 Nxg7 12. Qd2 $18) 8. dxe5 Nc6 9. hxg6 hxg6 10. c3 $1 {This move is
the point behind the whole concept. White is ready to sacrifice e5-pawn in
order to transfer his queen to the kingside via the 4th rank.} (10. Qe2 {
was the only move that I was considering in the game, but Black has enough
resources after} Qd5 $1 {preventing the transfer of white queen to e4 or c4.}
11. Qc4 Qxc4 12. Nxc4 b5 $132) 10... Nxe5 ({Black can try to prevent the queen
manoeuvre in several ways, but all of them fail to impress:} 10... Bg4 11. Qa4
Qd7 12. Bb5 $16) ({or:} 10... Qd7 11. Qe2 $1 (11. Qa4 Qg4 {is the idea.}) 11...
Qd5 {The crucial difference compared to a similar position with the pawn on c2
is that d4-square is covered, so Black has no counterplay with Bg4 and Nd4.} (
11... Qe6 12. Ng5 Qxe5 13. Nh7 $16 {wins the exchange.}) {After} 12. Nc4 $16 {
followed by Bf4, White is fully in control, with good attacking chances on the
