1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2 Bg7 4. e4 d6 {This is the classical King's Indian
approach as Black prevents 5.e5. In this chapter, we will look at the basic
continuation} 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O {Here, Black has several plans. If he goes for
the setup with ...e5, then I believe that the best square for the knight is}
Nc6 $1 {This is the most natural and active way to develop the knight since we
are ready to attack d4-pawn with 7...e5 next. The point is that d4-d5 advance
does not look promising for White due to an awkward position of knight on d2.}
(6... Nbd7 {is the alternative way to develop, but, as we will discuss in
CHAPTER 4, the positions arising after} 7. a4 e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 (8... dxe5 9. b4
$36) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Nc4 $14 {are generally quite pleasant for White.}) 7. c3
(7. d5 $6 Nb4 8. Be2 a5 $132) ({If White anticipates 7...e5 with} 7. a4 {then}
e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 $5 {makes a difference compared to 6...Nbd7 because White
cannot keep expanding on the queenside with 9.b4. The knight is placed much
more actively on c6, so Black has decent counterplay. For example:} 9. Nc4 (9.
Bb5 Nd4) 9... Nh5) 7... e5 {White has a number of options here. The most
popular choice is} 8. dxe5 {White clarifies the pawn structure in the centre
and plans to gradually build up the initiative on the queenside in a
symmetrical position. It used to be a pet line of young American GM Jeffery
Xiong.} ({It is also possible to keep the central tension with} 8. Re1 a5 $5 {
This is quite a typical move in this kind of structure. Black is gaining space
on the queenside and trying to provoke a symmetrical response from White. If
White indeed responds with a2-a4, then Black would be able to occupy the weak
b4-square with his knight after exchanging the pawns on d4.} (8... Nd7 {
can be played with a similar idea, but it is less flexible.} 9. Nb3 a5 $5 10.
a4 exd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 {although White would keep a slight edge with} 12. Bg5 Nf6
13. Bb1 h6 14. Bd2 $14) ({The alternative approach is to play on the kingside:
} 8... Nh5 9. Nb3 Bg4 10. Be2 Re8 11. h3 Bc8 12. Bg5 Bf6 13. Be3 $14 {but
White had everything under control in 1-0 (64) Timofeev,A (2589) -Kazhgaleyev,
M (2587) St Petersburg 2018}) 9. dxe5 {The simplest solution, though White can
hardly play for an advantage this way. Compared to a similar position from the
main line, ...a5 is clearly a more useful move for Black than Re1 is for White.
} (9. h3 {keeps the tension but allows Black to force some concessions in the
centre with} exd4 (9... Nh5 $5 10. dxe5 Nf4 {is an interesting alternative.}
11. Bb5 Nxe5 12. Nf1 Qf6 $132 {1/2 (36) Ritter,M (2448) -Bonin,J (2413) Nassau
2000}) (9... Bd7 {is rather passive, though. White had better chances after}
10. Nf1 Nh5 11. Bc2 h6 12. Ne3 $14 {1-0 (40) Aronian,L (2803) -Giri,A (2734)
Beijing 2013}) 10. cxd4 Nd7 {There is no 11.Nb3 now, so White has to play} 11.
d5 Nce5 12. Bf1 {Black has cleared the long diagonal for his bishop and I
would suggest that we continue} a4 $5 (12... Re8 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Nb3 c5 $13 {
0-1 (59) Ziska,H (2533) -Zubov, A (2601) Riga 2019}) 13. Rb1 c6 $132 {with
very good counterplay on the queenside.}) (9. a4 {stops the queenside
expansion, but at the same time, allows Black to play} exd4 $1 10. cxd4 Nb4 11.
Bb1 Re8 $132 {keeping the pressure against white pawn center with 12...Bg4 or
12...b6, 13...Bb7 next. 1/2 (26) Kovacevic, B (2453) -Kotronias,V (2506)
Zagreb 2019}) (9. Nf1 {is premature as it allows Black to play ...Bg4, so after
} exd4 {White is forced to play} 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. cxd4 c5 $132) 9... Nxe5 10.
Nxe5 dxe5 11. Nc4 Qe7 12. a4 Rd8 $11 {1/2 (19) Alekseev, E (2645) -Zubov,A 
(2601) Riga 2019}) (8. h3 {is another way to keep the tension, but Black can
continue in a similar fashion} a5 $5 ({Once again,} 8... Nh5 {is not as
promising. White keeps a solid central control with} 9. Nb3 a5 10. a4 exd4 (
10... Nf4 $2 {only compromises Black's pawn structure.} 11. Bxf4 exf4 12. Re1
h6 13. Nbd2 $16 {1-0 (57) Hansen,S (2603) -Harika,D (2524) Reykjavik 2011}) 11.
Nbxd4 Ne5 12. Bc2 $14) 9. a4 (9. Re1 {transposes to 8.Re1 line}) 9... exd4 10.
Nxd4 Nd7 (10... d5 $5 $132) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nf3 Ba6 $11 {1/2 (44) Wierzbicki,
J (2199) -Rakotomaharo,F (2422) Berlin 2018}) ({Finally, closing the center
with} 8. d5 {leads to a pretty good version of the KID for Black.} Ne7 9. Re1
Nh5 10. Nf1 Kh8 $132) 8... Nxe5 $5 {Since black knight has limited mobility on
c6, it is better to exchange it here.} ({Alternatively,} 8... dxe5 9. Nc4 Qe7 {
1/2 (26) Mirzoev,A (2477) -Grigoryan,K (2571) Tashkent 2019} 10. b4 $14 {
would be pleasant for White.}) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Nc4 {The knight is typically
placed the most actively on this square. White has a couple of ideas to exert
positional pressure, so Black needs to play accurately to keep the balance.} ({
The alternative development scheme is:} 10. Nf3 Qe7 11. a4 Rd8 12. Qe2 a5 13.
Bc4 {but Black is absolutely fine after} h6 14. Re1 b6 15. Be3 Ng4 16. Bc1 Nf6
17. Be3 Ng4 18. Bc1 {1/2 (18) Karjakin,S (2772) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2732) Loo
2014}) 10... Qe7 {This is the most flexible move, clearing d8-square for the
rook and keeping options for the knight open.} (10... Nh5 $5 {also makes sense,
trying to provoke some weaknesses on the kingside.} 11. g3 (11. a4 {allows
Black to win the bishop pair for free with} Nf4 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. h3 Be6 $15 {
1/2 (18) Nanu, C (2506) -Kurnosov, I (2602) Budva 2009}) (11. Re1 Nf4 12. Bf1 {
on the other hand, preserves the bishop pair, but allows Black to activate his
pieces with} Qf6 $13) 11... Qe7 12. Qe2 ({In the following game, White tried
to obtain the initiative by developing the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal} 12.
Re1 Be6 13. Qc2 Rad8 14. b3 Rfe8 15. a4 a6 16. Ba3 {However, Black seemed to
have created sufficient counterplay on the other flank with} Qg5 17. h4 Qf6 {
and White already had to be careful because of his multiple weaknesses.} 18.
Rad1 (18. Na5 $2 Nxg3 $1 19. fxg3 Qf3 $40) 18... Bg4 {1/2 (18) Erdos,V (2604)
-Berkes, F (2661) Hungary 2019}) (12. b3 Rd8 13. Qe2 {is an attempt to improve
on the previous game by keeping the queen closer to the kingside, but Black is
doing fine, nevertheless, after} Bh3 14. Rd1 Nf6 $11) 12... Rd8 13. Rd1 Be6 14.
Be3 {The bishop is placed better here than on a3 since it controls both flanks.
Black needs to play} a5 $1 {now to keep the balance} ({since} 14... Bf6 {
allows White to take a positional initiative on the queenside with} 15. Na5 c6
16. b4 $14 {1/2 (45) Xiong,J (2650) -Arribas Lopez,A (2460) Irving 2018}) 15.
a4 Nf6 16. f3 (16. Nxe5 $2 Bb3) 16... Nd7 $11) 11. Qe2 Rd8 12. Rd1 ({Another
playable option is} 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 {The pin seems slightly unpleasant for
Black, though perhaps he can solve his problems by concrete means:} g5 $5 ({
White kept some pressure in the following game:} 13... b6 14. Rfd1 Bb7 15. Ne3
a5 16. a4 h5 {and here, the simplest was} 17. h3 (17. Bc4 Bh6 18. f3 Rxd1+ 19.
Rxd1 Rd8 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Bxd5 $13 {1/2 (42) Xiong,J (2640) -Shankland,S (2668)
Saint Louis 2018}) 17... Bh6 18. Qf3 $14) 14. Bg3 Nh5 $1 {The point. After} 15.
Qxh5 Rxd3 16. Qe2 Rd8 17. Ne3 f6 {White's control over the f5-square has only
a symbolic meaning. Black is fine after} 18. f3 ({or} 18. Nf5 Qf7 $11) 18...
Be6 19. Nf5 Qf7 $11 {followed by ...Bf8, etc.}) 12... a5 $1 {In general, we
can conclude that this move should be played sooner or later in this structure.
Black not only takes up space on the queenside, but also prevents White's
important ideas such as b2-b4 and Nc4-a5.} (12... Bg4 {is also possible,
provoking some kingside weaknesses, but after} 13. f3 Be6 14. Be3 {it is
essential to play} Nh5 $5 (14... Ne8 {is inaccurate because it enables White
to seize the initiative on the queenside with} 15. Na5 c6 16. b4 $14 {1-0 (40)
Xiong,J (2651) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2780) chess.com INT 2018}) 15. g3 a5 $1 {
and Black should be fine after that, for example} 16. a4 Nf6 17. Bf2 Nd7 $13)
13. a4 h6 $5 {It makes sense to prevent the Bg5 pin now that the bishop on d3
is overprotected.} ({In the event of} 13... Be6 {White could go} 14. Bg5 h6 15.
Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 {and now Black would not have the tactical resource ...Nh5 as
