1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Bd3 {In this chapter, we will
discuss positions arising after} c5 $5 {This is a markedly different approach
compared to the one discussed in CHAPTER 2. Black attacks the white centre
with the c- instead of the e-pawn, trying to clear the long diagonal for his
dark-squared bishop. It is also important to talk about move orders. It seems
to me that it is more precise for Black to play this move at once than one
