1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2 c5 {This is a logical attempt to undermine the
white centre, which might particularly appeal to black players who like to
play the Hedgehog setup.} 4. dxc5 {There is hardly a better alternative since
4.d5 is not an option. White gives up his central control to a degree but
gains several developing tempi in return since Black's best way to recoup the
pawn is} Qa5 5. a3 Qxc5 6. b4 Qc7 7. Bb2 Bg7 {At this point White needs to
make an important choice. The two main setups at his disposal are the
g3-fianchetto or to develop the bishop to e2/d3 after e3.} 8. e3 {White can
also postpone this decision by playing 8.c4 first, but we will start with this
move for the sake of simplicity.} ({The second option is} 8. c4 O-O 9. g3 b6
10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O d6 {when both sides have a double fianchetto setup. White
holds a space advantage, but Black is very flexible in these Hedgehog
