1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2 d5 $1 {This classical way of meeting 3.Nbd2 is the
critical variation from a theoretical point of view, posing White the most
problems to fight for an advantage. e2-e4 is not an option any more, so White
typically turns to the queenside play with b2-b4, simultaneously stopping
Black's ...c5 break. However, the move orders also matter and White can choose
whether to start with 4.b4 or 4.e3, as well as when to push c2-c4. In this
chapter, we will explore some of them.} 4. b4 $5 {This move is much less
popular compared to 4.e3, although it is not so clear why that is the case.
Black has only one relevant possibility to try to take advantage of this move
order, otherwise, we usually get a transposition into positions covered in the
last two chapters.} (4. e3 {is the most obvious and popular move and we will
take it as the main line, as well. However, it is important to keep in mind
that Back has a decent option to prevent 5.b4,} a5 $5 {Even though this move
looks a bit dubious from the point of view of classical development, it is not
easy at all to prove that.} (4... Nc6 $6 {also prevents 5.b4, but it seems
like a passive way to treat this position. White obtained a slight edge
without much problem by playing} 5. b3 Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 a5 8. a3 b6 9. O-O
e6 10. c4 $14 {1/2 (38) So,W (2792) -Svidler,P (2768) Wijk aan Zee 2018}) (4...
c5 $6 {looks similar to 3... c5, but this is a clearly better version for
White.} 5. dxc5 Bg7 ({The point is that if Black plays} 5... Qa5 {then after}
6. a3 Qxc5 7. b4 Qc3 (7... Qc7 8. Bb2 Bg7 9. c4 $14 {is similar.}) 8. Rb1 Bg7
9. Bb2 Qc7 {White opens the centre favourably with} 10. c4 {Black would rather
have the pawn on d6, as we have seen in CHAPTER 5.} O-O 11. Rc1 Qd8 {1-0 (29)
Fressinet,L (2633) -Gareyev,T (2591) Bastia 2019 Here, I suggest a new move}
12. h3 $5 {with the idea to prevent ...Bg4. Black faces serious problems with
a lack of space for his pieces after} Nc6 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Be2
$16 {Meanwhile, White has an easy plan 0-0, Qb3, Rfd1 with a strong pressure
